SIMPLE: send
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Send
<hw>Send</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Sent</conjf> <pr>(<?/)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Sending</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>sendan</ets>; akin to
OS. <ets>sendian</ets>, D. <ets>zenden</ets>, G. <ets>senden</ets>, OHG.
<ets>senten</ets>, Icel. <ets>senda</ets>, Sw. <ets>s⟦aum⟧nda</ets>,
Dan. <ets>sende</ets>, Goth. <ets>sandjan</ets>, and to Goth.
<ets>sinp</ets> a time (properly, a going), ga<ets>sinpa</ets>
companion, OHG. <ets>sind</ets> journey, AS. <ets>s⟦imac⟧<?/</ets>,
Icel. <ets>sinni</ets> a walk, journey, a time. W. <ets>hynt</ets> a
way, journey, OIr. <ets>s<?/t</ets>. Cf. <er>Sense</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To cause to go in any manner; to dispatch; to
commission or direct to go; <as>as, to <ex>send</ex> a
messenger</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I have not <qex>sent</qex> these prophets, yet they ran.</q>
<rj><qau>Jer. xxiii. 21.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I proceeded forth and came from God; neither came I of myself, but
he <qex>sent</qex> me.</q> <rj><qau>John viii. 42.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Servants, <qex>sent</qex> on messages, stay out somewhat longer
than the message requires.</q> <rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To give motion to; to cause to be borne or carried;
to procure the going, transmission, or delivery of; <as>as, to
<ex>send</ex> a message</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He . . . <qex>sent</qex> letters by posts on horseback.</q>
<rj><qau>Esther viii. 10.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>O <qex>send</qex> out thy light an thy truth; let them lead
me.</q> <rj><qau>Ps. xliii. 3.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To emit; to impel; to cast; to throw; to hurl;
<as>as, to <ex>send</ex> a ball, an arrow, or the like</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To cause to be or to happen; to bestow; to inflict;
to grant; -- sometimes followed by a dependent proposition.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧God <xex>send</xex> him well!⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Lord shall <qex>send</qex> upon thee cursing, vexation, and
rebuke.</q> <rj><qau>Deut. xxviii. 20.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And <qex>sendeth</qex> rain on the just and on the unjust.</q>
<rj><qau>Matt. v. 45.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>God <qex>send</qex> your mission may bring back peace.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir W. Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Send</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Send
<hw>Send</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
dispatch an agent or messenger to convey a message, or to do an
errand.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>See ye how this son of a murderer hath <qex>sent</qex> to take
away my head?</q> <rj><qau>2 Kings vi. 32.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>To pitch; <as>as, the ship
<ex>sends</ex> forward so violently as to endanger her masts</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Totten.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To send for</b></col>, <cd>to request or require by
message to come or be brought.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Send</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Send
<hw>Send</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>The impulse of a
wave by which a vessel is carried bodily.</def> <altsp>[Written also
<asp>scend</asp>.]</altsp> <au>W. C. Russell.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧The
<xex>send</xex> of the sea⟦rdquo⟧. <rj><au>Longfellow.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sendal</ent>⟦br⟧
